Question 3:

Mapping aesthetics to CATEGORICAL variables:

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color=fl))

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy, shape=drv))

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy, size=class))
## Warning: Using size for a discrete variable is not advised.

Mapping aesthetics to CONTINUOUS variables:

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy, color=cty))

ggplot(data=mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x=displ, y=hwy, size=cty))

From the above code chunks, we see a few differences between mapping categorical variables versus mapping continuous variables. Most notably, R will not allow us to map continuous variables to shapes, and it advises that we shouldnt map categorical variables to sizes. In terms of mapping color, the catgorical variables are mapped to a rather, well, categorical palette. On the other hand, continous variables are mapped to a monochromatic/analagous palette.

Question 3

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(cyl ~ .)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

The . code makes it so the x or y axis is reapeated in every facet. In other words, we see how the coordinates compare within each facet alone, rather than amongst all facets. I think its visual comparison sake? Again, Im very bad at explaining these things.

Question 4

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

With faceting, its easier to visualize the trends WITHIN each category. With color mapping, however, its easier to visualize the trends BETWEEN each category. Faceting is better for studying the categories as individual beings; color mapping is better for studying all the categories as one whole being. Ugh, why is it so hard to verbalize these things???????

Question 5

?facet_wrap

The ncol and nrow determine the dimensions of the entire collection of subplots. For example, the previous graph has nrow=2 and ncol=4. Facet grid is one plot divided (AKA: one, shared axis), whereas facet wrap is a collection of subplots (AKA: axes that ARENT shared). Thus, with facet_grid, there arent multiple plots the organize.

Before looking at this codes output, I imagined it would be dot plot displaying the trend between displ and hwy. The estimated curve of the points trend would be represented by a line; the points would be color coded by their drv. Question 3

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv))
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = drv), show.legend = FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'loess' and formula 'y ~ x'

show.legend = FALSEhides the legend. Removing that codeshows the legend! The legend labels the meanings behind the shape, color, etc. mapping you used to classify certain points. Its all pretty self-explanatory, to be honest.

The se argument refers to the standard error of the fitted line estimation.

Question 1

ggplot(data = diamonds) + 
  stat_summary(
    mapping = aes(x = cut, y = depth),
    fun.ymin = min,
    fun.ymax = max,
    fun.y = median
  )

That stat_summary() function seems to resemble the pointrange geom. Anyway, heres the recreation! (I admit, I found what code would recreate the graph through stackoverflow):

?geom_point

ggplot(data=diamonds) +
  geom_pointrange( 
    mapping = aes(x=cut, y=depth), 
    stat="summary",
    fun.ymin = min,
    fun.ymax = max,
    fun.y = median
  )

Question 4

?stat_smooth()

Wellokay. Apparently stat_smooth() is essentially the same thing as geom_smooth(), BUT stat_smooth() is for more peculiar cases? The help section states Use geom_smooth unless you want to display the results with a non-standard geom. stat_smooth() includes some arguments geom_smooth() does not. For examplen, span, fullrange, level, method.args.
